[section=A Fox in the Stable: 2011]

My highly anticipated video featuring my Taurin Fox character and the stallion I recently modeled for my "Horseplay" video.

"Download as MP4 file (104MB)":http://www.taurinfox.com/animations/fox-in-the-stable.mp4

[/section]

[section=A Fox in the Stable]

Download as MP4: http://www.taurinfox.com/animations/fox-in-the-stable.mp4

A full-screen mode has also been added, but is not supported through FA. To use this function, please download the SWF file and open it from your PC (note, the source video file will not be downloaded, so an internet connection will still be needed to view the animation through the downloaded SWF).

**

For everyone complaining about the motion appearing slow: I have noticed that certain computers and video players aren't able to play the video back at full speed. I've released a smaller version to help with people experiencing this problem:

http://www.taurinfox.com/animations/fox-in-the-stable-sm.mp4

This animation has been in the works for several years, and is finally done! Featuring my Taurin Fox character, and the stallion I recently modeled for my "Horseplay" video, the animation is based entirely on this 2-part painting I created back in 2002:
https://www.furaffinity.net/view/3900853/
https://www.furaffinity.net/view/3905893/

I used a new rendering technique which allowed me to create a highly-detailed background with reflected lighting, which rendered (relatively) quickly, and didn’t produce noisy or flickering results. The process involved rendering the scene in 5 separate passes in 3DS Max, and then compositing them in After Effects. I’m extremely happy with the results!

The music track was provided by "Fann,":https://www.furaffinity.net/user/fann and he did an amazing job on it! If you enjoy his work, please check out his FA page:
https://www.furaffinity.net/user/fann/

The animation was rendered at a resolution of 1920 x 1080, with the intention of releasing it on a Blu-ray disc. I’m putting the finishing touches on that disc now, and I’ll make a journal post later today with more details.

I’m thrilled to finally be releasing this one =) I feel that it’s my best animation work to date by far!

The video can be downloaded directly as an MP4 file here:
http://www.taurinfox.com/animations/fox-in-the-stable.mp4

Enjoy!

Support me on Patreon at https://www.patreon.com/taurinfox
Join me on Twitter at https://twitter.com/taurin_fox
Watch my weekly live streams at https://picarto.tv/taurinfox
And view my archive of work at http://www.taurinfox.com

[/section]

I finally completed the animation that I have been working on for the past few months! It was a huge project, I bit off way more than I can chew, but overall I think it came out great! The animation itself took around 38 hours to render, with some additional hours for post-processing.

Considering just how much time this animation took, I am probably not doing another one of these proportions in the near future. Blender is also partially a nightmare with scenes of this complexity. The models and environment are loaded from different files. That often causes annoying issues such as physics not properly caching, motion paths not being available, and many more.

Artist can be found on:
Twitter: https://twitter.com/gobanire
Furaffinity: https://www.furaffinity.net/user/gobanire/
Patreon: https://patreon.com/gobanire

[section=Hit the Showers (new animation) - by taurinfox]

Hit the Showers is now live! 

Kish and Taurin enjoy a steamy encounter in the Alphafox Resorts changing room! 

Even though it took a lot longer to finish than expected, I’m really happy with how this one turned out. Thanks to engagement and feedback from viewers, Hit the Showers makes heavy use of motion capture, dialogue, cloth and fluid simulations, as well as rendering improvements. 

Special thanks to Kish and Asher for doing the audio engineering, and to Asher for providing the music track. All sound effects were recorded by them specifically for this animation. Meticulous editing and painstaking went into producing the soundscape. During the audio phase, Asher spent a lot of time producing the soundtrack Aquatic Endeavor to make it flow with the action on screen as well as the mood. 

Many thanks to all of my supporters on Patreon, who really have made this and my other projects possible.
